thread.title: $A steady as traders look overseas

title: $A steady as traders look overseas
text:
Mon, Sep 28, 2015, 8:39 PM NZDT - New Zealand Markets closed $A steady as traders look overseas AAP – 20 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar is steady as traders wait for more direction on the timing of a US interest rate hike. 
At 1700 AEST on Monday, the local unit was trading at 70.33 US cents, the same level as at the end of local trade on Friday. 
The Aussie dollar moved within a narrow range as traders look ahead to speeches from four US Federal Reserve Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) members, US RBC Capital Markets currency strategist Michael Turner said. 
"There is not much desire to get involved today given there was no weekend news and no domestic data out today," he said. 
"New York Fed President William Dudley's address tonight will be a fairly key event because he is usually a good guide on the FOMC. 
"Then there is US payroll numbers out on Friday night which will give us further ideas on whether there will be an October rate hike." 
At 1700 AEST one Australian dollar was buying 84.72 Japanese yen, level with Friday and 62.89 euro cents, down from 63.02 euro cents. 
It was also a quiet session on the bond market. 
At 1630 AEST on Monday, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.280 (implying a yield of 2.720 per cent), up from 97.270 (2.730 per cent) on Friday.
